98
00:07:18,800 --> 00:07:23,520
Can you break this down a little bit more about why this works and why you did this?

99
00:07:23,520 --> 00:07:30,080
>> The curse of being a software developer is that it's so easy to fall in love with an idea.

100
00:07:30,080 --> 00:07:32,319
And I've done this so many times before.

101
00:07:32,319 --> 00:07:38,160
Too often we just get excited about that invention without making sure that it's actually like a painkiller.

102
00:07:38,160 --> 00:07:42,319
So as an entrepreneur we always want to be selling a painkiller, not a vitamin.

103
00:07:42,319 --> 00:07:44,800
A vitamin is a nice to have.

104
00:07:44,800 --> 00:07:49,199
A painkiller is something you have to have and it's going to sell a lot better.

105
00:07:49,199 --> 00:07:55,440
The traditional advice with startups is to go and talk to your friends and say, "What do you think about this idea?

106
00:07:55,440 --> 00:07:56,560
Give me feedback."

107
00:07:56,560 --> 00:08:03,599
Maybe the next level of advice would be to say, "How much would you pay for this tool if it existed?"

108
00:08:03,599 --> 00:08:06,240
I actually think that that feedback is not good enough.

109
00:08:06,240 --> 00:08:10,800
In fact, it's actually quite dangerous because it lets you think you have validation.

110
00:08:10,800 --> 00:08:16,879
So, you go in a hole for 3 months or however long it takes to build this thing and then you pop up for air and you say,

111
00:08:16,879 --> 00:08:18,160
"Hey guys, it's ready."

112
00:08:18,160 --> 00:08:30,080
And the problem with that approach, they say, you know, I would be willing to pay $20 a month if I didn't have this other subscription or I would be willing to pay once I get this check-in from my old

113
00:08:30,080 --> 00:08:30,479
company.

114
00:08:30,479 --> 00:08:32,320
And I've seen this happen so many times.

115
00:08:32,320 --> 00:08:36,800
So, the only way to really get validation is to collect money from people.

116
00:08:36,800 --> 00:08:42,000
And the faster you can get to that, the more likely it is that your startup is going to succeed.

117
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:43,039
>> Okay, that's amazing.

118
00:08:43,039 --> 00:08:48,560
I think it's one of the best pieces of advice for anybody bootstrapping anything with their own cash.

119
00:08:48,560 --> 00:08:52,080
What I really want to get from you, and I think a lot of people watching this would be wondering,

120
00:08:52,080 --> 00:08:58,959
if you were to give advice to someone watching right now on how to do that, what would be your exact playbook if you had to start over from scratch today?

121
00:08:58,959 --> 00:09:03,360
>> Well, step one is you have to build an audience because if you don't have an audience,

122
00:09:03,360 --> 00:09:05,120
you don't have anyone to sell to.

123
00:09:05,120 --> 00:09:07,760
People buy because they trust you.

124
00:09:07,760 --> 00:09:13,360
And especially today when it's so easy to create products that there's a million products out there.

125
00:09:13,360 --> 00:09:16,800
People buy based on believing in a brand or a person.

126
00:09:16,800 --> 00:09:23,279
Post the raw, you know, build in public type stories of you with your thought process and what you're doing.

127
00:09:23,279 --> 00:09:25,839
And that will help establish trust with people.

128
00:09:25,839 --> 00:09:31,680
The way I did that was just by putting out free things of value that took me time to create,

129
00:09:31,680 --> 00:09:33,920
but I knew would be helpful to other people.

130
00:09:33,920 --> 00:09:39,519
in addition to just showing up and being really authentic about who I was and why I was there.

131
00:09:39,519 --> 00:09:45,279
That alone can get you an audience of people that trust you and are engaged with you.

132
00:09:45,279 --> 00:09:47,040
And that really is the first step.

133
00:09:47,040 --> 00:09:53,120
Step two is you've got to set up an email list and start communicating with people at least once a week.

134
00:09:53,120 --> 00:10:01,440
So, while your social media can be a great way to kind of interact with new people, your email list is really where you're building that trust.

135
00:10:01,440 --> 00:10:09,839
And what's cool is that when you start emailing people, they will email you back and you start this dialogue and you can start to talk to them about your idea.

136
00:10:09,839 --> 00:10:16,640
You can even use your email list to put out your ideas, get the replies back as your feedback on how to improve your idea.

137
00:10:16,640 --> 00:10:22,480
Show up, do that weekly because when it's time to hit up that email list in order to,

138
00:10:22,480 --> 00:10:26,320
you know, start your pre-sale, you're going to need that level of engagement.

139
00:10:26,320 --> 00:10:32,160
So step three is you've got to do the math on what validation would look like for you.

140
00:10:32,160 --> 00:10:41,760
In my case, I knew I needed to make about $20,000 to fund, let's say, 3 months of my life in order to work on this thing.

141
00:10:41,760 --> 00:10:49,200
And so I worked out how many people I would need based on my target price point of what I thought this type of customer would pay.

142
00:10:49,200 --> 00:10:51,839
And that led me to 50 people to buy.

143
00:10:51,839 --> 00:10:59,440
And so then I worked out the math of how big does my email list need to be in order to potentially get 50 buyers.

144
00:10:59,440 --> 00:11:01,360
And so I thought about conversion rates.

145
00:11:01,360 --> 00:11:03,440
You know, it's obviously going to depend.

146
00:11:03,440 --> 00:11:11,920
But that gives you a very scientific way of understanding, you know, what kind of audience that you need to build before you're ready to start this pre-sale.

147
00:11:11,920 --> 00:11:14,399
Step four is we're ready to do the pre-sale.

148
00:11:14,399 --> 00:11:21,440
Now, you've got to get aggressive about this because there's no one who's going to be excited about your product unless you make them excited.

149
00:11:21,440 --> 00:11:25,600
So, you've got to set up an email sequence every single day for seven days.

150
00:11:25,600 --> 00:11:30,079
Start teasing out the benefits of this product that you're building.

151
00:11:30,079 --> 00:11:34,640
And yes, you can talk about features, too, but it's really about the benefits for them.

152
00:11:34,640 --> 00:11:39,360
Really get emotional and talk about how this benefit is going to impact their life.

153
00:11:39,360 --> 00:11:44,160
And the more that you can do this, the more likely it is that people are going to convert.

154
00:11:44,160 --> 00:11:50,079
And towards that last day, really start hitting home this concept of the pre-sale that's launching.

155
00:11:50,079 --> 00:11:52,079
Do not give any details away yet.

156
00:11:52,079 --> 00:11:52,959
Just give a date.

157
00:11:52,959 --> 00:11:59,040
On the launch day, you've got to have several emails queued up so people know exactly when it's going live.

158
00:11:59,040 --> 00:12:03,040
You've got to have reminders when the pre-sale is about to end.

159
00:12:03,040 --> 00:12:07,360
And you've got to be firing on all cylinders on all of your social media channels.

160
00:12:07,360 --> 00:12:09,600
You've got to be really visible during that time.

161
00:12:09,600 --> 00:12:16,240
And if you work really, really hard and engage with people, it's an incredible thing when you actually pull off a pre-sale like that.

162
00:12:16,240 --> 00:12:22,800
So, a key part of the pre-sale is to have an offer so good that people can't help it but say yes.

163
00:12:22,800 --> 00:12:27,120
And if you follow Alex Hormosy's $und00 million offers, he talks about this a ton.

164
00:12:27,120 --> 00:12:34,560
For me, for the first 10 customers, might have not even been profitable, but I knew it was something that people would say yes to.

165
00:12:34,560 --> 00:12:39,440
I also wanted to give people total security and comfort in their purchase.

166
00:12:39,440 --> 00:12:43,600
So, the way that I did that was by offering a money back guarantee.

167
00:12:43,600 --> 00:12:48,480
So the entire time in between when the pre-sale happened and when the product was delivered,

168
00:12:48,480 --> 00:12:50,079
they could ask for their money back.

169
00:12:50,079 --> 00:12:53,440
People had the confidence in knowing that they could get their money back.

170
00:12:53,440 --> 00:12:58,720
Especially for someone who's new in the space, they were able to go ahead and make that purchasing decision.

171
00:12:58,720 --> 00:13:03,760
So for whatever your product is, think of an offer so good that people can't help but to say yes.

